Ames Housing Model Analysis, Part 2

Steven Slezak

31 March 2018

In this second part of the Ames data modeling exercise, we continue from the regression benchmark laid down in the first part and further explore feature selection using methods such as cross validation and Principle Component Regression. We will also use other models – ridge regression, the lasso, decision trees, random forest, bagging, boosting, and SVM – to work the data and develop predictions regarding house prices in Ames.

We are working with the same Ames data set, but it will be structured a bit differently in this part of the study. Previously, we combined the Kaggle train.csv and test.csv, performed data preparation, then separated the files again. In this part, we will work with the train.csv file, which we will split into training and validation sets in order to train and tune models and parameters.

This is because that type of material is not found in the observation used in the train.csv file, though it is in the combined data file. Since it is missing now we will just drop the feature from our current list, reducing it from 16 to 15.

We need to create a couple objects and a function we will call upon later in the analysis, so let’s take a minute to do that now.

AmesTrDumScaleDFShort$id <- 1:nrow(AmesTrDumScaleDFShort)
lm.train <- AmesTrDumScaleDFShort %>% sample_frac(0.5)
lm.test <- anti_join(AmesTrDumScaleDFShort, lm.train, by = 'id')

predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id, ...) {
        form = as.formula(object$call [[2]])
        mat = model.matrix(form, newdata)
        coefi = coef(object, id = id)
        xvars = names(coefi)
        mat[, xvars] %*% coefi
}

3 Using k-fold Cross Validation in Feature Selection

Now we are in a position to continue the analysis.

In the first section we performed some feature selection using a number of different methods. Next we will continue with a cross validation method. In particular, this method is based on k-fold cross validation, in which subsets are selected from each of the k training sets available to the program. There are 15 features to work with so k will be set to that number. Our purpose here is not so much selecting a new set of features to work with as it is using this method to confirm the feature set we have been using looks good from this perspective.

k = 15
set.seed(805)
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(AmesTrDumScaleDFShort), replace = TRUE)
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, 15, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:15)))
for (j in 1:k) {
        best.fit = regsubsets(SalePrice ~ ., data = AmesTrDumScaleDFShort[folds != j, ],
                              nvmax = 16)
        for (i in 1:15) {
                pred = predict.regsubsets(best.fit, AmesTrDumScaleDFShort[folds == j, ], id = i)
                cv.errors[j, i] =  mean((AmesTrDumScaleDFShort$SalePrice[folds == j] - pred)^2)
        }
}
## Reordering variables and trying again:

We can calculate the cross validation errors, average them, and plot the results against the number of variables, the k-folds we are working with. We can see 14 or 15 minimizes error. Cross validation indicates the number of features we are working with is appropriate. We will calculate the coefficients for the features at that level. We can use these to validate our earlier findings and build a model.

mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)

4 Creating a Ridge Regression Analysis

We want to build models using different methods to see if we can improve the performance of our benchmark regression model. We can start with a ridge regression. A grid will be used to calculate a range of values we will employ to tune the parameters of the model. The goal is to find the right “penalty” for improving model performance. With the ridge, this is known as an L1 penalty.

xx <- model.matrix(SalePrice ~ ., data = AmesTrDumScaleDFShort)[, -1]

Due to the structure of the grid we employed, the ridge model creates a 17 x 100 matrix of values for the model’s coefficients. Each vector is associated with a specific lambda value. We can use that information to calculate the RMSE for the ridge at that particular lambda. Though low, this is not necessarily the most appropriate RMSE. We are tuning the lambda value. If we tune that properly we will get the most appropriate RMSE, which isn’t always the lowest RMSE value.

5 Creating the Lasso

The lasso is very similar to a ridge regression, the main difference being the penalty applied to the model. The lasso uses an L2 penalty.

As with the ridge regression, we start by defining the model and examining its output.

The first graph demonstrates how the application of the penalty impacts the coefficients of the model. The higher the penalty, it seems, the lower the value of the coefficients. The second graph is the log of lambda plot (as above) for the lasso.

lasso.mod <- glmnet(xx[train, ], yy[train], alpha = 1, lambda = grid)
plot(lasso.mod)

set.seed(805)
cv.out <- cv.glmnet(xx[train, ], yy[train], alpha = 1)
plot(cv.out)

We use a similar process as before to define the best lambda for tuning the lasso model. a lambda of 947.7 yields an RMSE of 31,877. This is very similar to the RMSE from the ridge (31,672) but not an improvement.

6 Performing Principle Components Regression on the Data

We can plot the error rate against both size and k. Again, we see 7 terminal nodes is the most appropriate decision tree model.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(cv.Ames$size, cv.Ames$dev, type = 'b')
plot(cv.Ames$k, cv.Ames$dev, type = 'b')

Using this information, we can construct a “pruned” tree (analagous to tuned model) and collect the results. Accuracy increases to 88.5% and the model utilizes only four features: YearBuilt, GrLivArea, LotArea, and TotalBsmtSF.

prune.Ames <- prune.misclass(tree.Ames, best = 7)
plot(prune.Ames)
text(prune.Ames, pretty = 0)

tree.pred <- predict(prune.Ames, Ames.test, type = 'class')
table(tree.pred, High.test)
##          High.test
## tree.pred  No Yes
##       No  322  49
##       Yes  35 322
(322 + 322) / 728
## [1] 0.8846

8 Fitting a Regression Tree

Our exploration of decision trees leads us to a point where we can fit a regression tree to the Ames data and calculate an MSRE. We start by deleted two unnecessary columns from the data, the id and High columns, and training the data against the test target SalePrice. Here, the tree is utilizing just five features: YearBuilt, GrLivArea, TotalBsmtSF, GarageArea, and KitchenQual_Ex.

DTRAmes <- DTAmes[, -c(17, 18)]
set.seed(805)
train <- sample(1:nrow(DTRAmes), nrow(DTRAmes) / 2)
tree.DTRAmes <- tree(SalePrice ~ ., DTRAmes, subset = train)
summary(tree.DTRAmes)

9 Creating a Random Forest Analysis (with Bagging)

Instead of using a single tree, we can build a “forest” of decision trees and average their results. This is known a “ensemble” modelling. “Bagging” is a special kind of random forest model, in which m = p. That is, in which the size of the sample predictors (m) is equal to the size of the ful set of predictors (p).

At this stage of the analysis, we can build the bagging model fairly quickly and examine its results. This model generated a “forest” of 500 decision trees and averaged the results. In doing so, it achieves an adjusted R2 of 83.2.

set.seed(805)
bag.DTRAmes <- randomForest(SalePrice ~ ., data = DTRAmes, subset = train, 
                            mtry = 18, importance = TRUE)
bag.DTRAmes
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = SalePrice ~ ., data = DTRAmes, mtry = 18,      importance = TRUE, subset = train) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 15
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 974450404
##                     % Var explained: 83.21

We use the model to generate predictions, plot the results, and calculate the RMSE. The RMSE is 32,047. This is competitive with the ridge regression but still not an improvement.

yhat.bag <- predict(bag.DTRAmes, newdata = DTRAmes[-train, ])
plot(yhat.bag, DTRAmes.test)
abline(0, 1)

mean((yhat.bag - DTRAmes.test)^2)

11 Creating a Random Forest Analysis (with Boosting)

Boosting is another twist on decision trees and random forests. It is an ensemble method, like random forests, but it is more useful in reducing variance and bias. In this case, we will run the boost as a Gaussian distribution because we are working with a regression problem. We also set the model to run a forest of 5000 trees. The first returns are a list of features ordered by importance.

set.seed(805)
boost.DTRAmes <- gbm(SalePrice ~ ., DTRAmes[train, ], distribution = 'gaussian',
                     n.trees = 5000, interaction.depth = 4, shrinkage = 0.2, verbose = FALSE)
summary(boost.DTRAmes)
